### throw vs throws

`throw` is used to explicitly throw an exception. `throws` is used to declare that a method may throw exceptions.

---

### The `throw` Keyword

Used inside a method to throw an exception:

```java
public void checkAge(int age) {
    if (age < 18) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Must be 18+");
    }
}
```

---

### The `throws` Keyword

Used in method signature to declare exceptions:

```java
public void readFile(String path) throws IOException {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);
}
```

---

### Key Differences

| Feature | throw | throws |
|---------|-------|--------|
| Location | Inside method body | Method signature |
| What it does | Actually throws exception | Declares possible exception |
| Number | Only one | Multiple comma-separated |
| Followed by | Throwable instance | Exception class names |

---

### Re-throwing Exceptions

```java
try {
    processFile();
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Logging...");
    throw e;  // re-throw
}
```

---

### Exception Chaining

```java
try {
    // code
} catch (IOException e) {
    throw new RuntimeException("Operation failed", e);  // cause = e
}
```

> **Key Point:** `throw` is followed by an actual exception object. `throws` is followed by exception class names in the method signature. If a method throws a checked exception, the caller must handle or declare it.

codeExample:
import java.io.*;

public class Main {
    // throws declaration
    public static void validate(int age) throws IllegalArgumentException {
        if (age < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age cannot be negative");
        }
        System.out.println("Valid age: " + age);
    }

    public static String readLineFromFile(String file) 
            throws IOException, FileNotFoundException {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
        return br.readLine();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            validate(-5);
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        try {
            readLineFromFile("nonexistent.txt");
        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("File not found: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("IO Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
